soft-delete vs hard-delete bloat benchmark
PostgreSQL 16.14 (Debian 16.14-1.pgdg13+1) on aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu
params: cycles=50 insert_batch=5000 remove_batch=4000 latency_iterations=300 seed=1234

EXPERIMENT 1  table/index bloat under churn (50 cycles, 6.7s)
  hard_delete_orders  total=22.84 MB  table=8.62 MB  secondary_index=9.06 MB  live=50000  dead=0
  soft_delete_orders  total=62.26 MB  table=41.85 MB  secondary_index=9.71 MB  live=250000  dead=0
  ratio (soft/hard): total=2.73x  table=4.86x  secondary_index=1.07x

EXPERIMENT 2  query latency after bloat accumulated
  hard_delete_orders   pk_lookup    p50=  0.2532ms  p95=  0.2904ms  p99=  0.5374ms  mean=  0.2613ms
  hard_delete_orders   active_rows  p50=  0.2995ms  p95=  0.4077ms  p99=  1.3317ms  mean=  0.3267ms
  soft_delete_orders   pk_lookup    p50=  0.2168ms  p95=  0.2560ms  p99=  0.6657ms  mean=  0.2255ms
  soft_delete_orders   active_rows  p50=  0.3253ms  p95=  1.3392ms  p99=  1.7629ms  mean=  0.4635ms
  active_rows p99 ratio (soft/hard) = 1.32x

EXPERIMENT 3  partial index fix
  soft_delete_original_index   p50=  0.3145ms  p95=  0.3468ms  p99=  0.5633ms  rows_removed_by_filter=209    index_size=9944.0 KB
  soft_delete_partial_index    p50=  0.3004ms  p95=  0.4660ms  p99=  0.7222ms  rows_removed_by_filter=0      index_size=1112.0 KB
  hard_delete_baseline         p50=  0.3297ms  p95=  0.9611ms  p99=  1.8645ms  rows_removed_by_filter=0      index_size=9280.0 KB
  partial index is 8.9x smaller than the full index (1112.0 KB vs 9944.0 KB)
  active_rows p99 improves 0.78x after adding the partial index (0.5633ms -> 0.7222ms)

